#N canvas 1970 50 1123 922 notes 0;
#X text 19 90 [fft~] computes the Fourier transform \, given the real and imaginary part of a complex-valued signal. Here the imaginary part is zero (the input is real-valued). The output is a (real \, imaginary) pair for each frequency from 0 to 128 (in units of SR/64)., f 140;
#X text 18 128 The [fft~] object has separate inlets for the real and imaginary parts of a complex-valued signal and outputs its Fourier transform \, again using separate outlets for the real and imaginary part. The transform is done on one block of samples (here the block size is 64 \, (Pd's default is 64). The outputs give the complex amplitudes of the harmonics of the input signal \, from DC up. The harmonics are tuned to the fundamental frequency of the analysis \, 1/128th of the sample rate. If the frequency (in harmonics) is an integer \, the result is two harmonics symmetric about the Nyquist frequency. Fractional frequencies spill across harmonics. Changing the initial phase rotates energy from real to imaginary and back., f 139;
#X text 17 235 BRINGING FFT CALCULATION INTO A SUBPATCH AS IN I02.Hann.window CAUSES CALCULATION ISSUE (RIPPLING AMPLITUDES \, ..) AT CERTAIN FREQUENCIES EVEN WITH HANN WINDOW ---> LATER CHECK WHY.. ---> KEEP BLOCK DEFINITION IN PARENT PATCH, f 122;
#X text 8 288 - CONTINUOUS FREQUENCY [1(CYCLE)/SEC = HZ]: HOW MUCH OF 1 CYCLE IS PASSED WITH EACH SECOND \; - DISCRETE FREQUENCY [1(CYCLE)/SAMPLE]: HOW MUCH OF 1 CYCLE IS PASSED AT EACH SAMPLE \; - IF DISCRETE FREQEUNCY == BLOCK-SIZE \, MEANS THAT WITH EACH SAMPLE WE HAVE 1 ROTATION -> ALWAYS 1 \; - FREQUENCY BINS: [0: (BLOCK-SIZE)-1] --> DISCRETE FREQUENCY INDICES \; - DISCRETE FUNDAMENTAL FREQUENCY: 1/(BLOCK-SIZE) [1/SAMPLE] \; - CONTINUOUS FUNDAMENTAL FREQUENCY: SR/(WINDOW-SIZE) [HZ==1/SEC] \;, f 102;
#X text 11 402 WHEN DISCRETE FREQUENCY INDEX = 1 (AND PHASE 0) FFT FIND THE FREQUENCY BINS AT 1 AND 127 (IN A 128 BLOCK-SIZE) ---> UNDERSTAND THIS BETTER ---> SINCE INPUT IS REAL SIGNAL \, IT IS CONSTRUCTED OF TWO OPPOSITELY ROTATING COMPLEX EXPONENTIALS. IN DFT A COMPLEX EXPONENTION ROTATING AT (-k0) IS EQUAL AND SHOWN WITH A COMPLEX EXPONENTIAL ROTATING AT (N-k0) DUE TO PERIODICITY OF EXAMINER FUNCTION (SEE PYTHON NOTEBOOK AND CHATGPT DISCUSSIONS), f 141;
#X text 12 489 TO GET CONTINUOUS FREQUENCY OF THE WINDOW BINS -> INDEX SHOULD BE MULTIPLIED BY SR/(WINDOW-SIZE), f 97;
#X text 11 612 IN GENERAL - BETTER TO KEEP THE SOUND SOURCE AND FFT IN SAME SUBPATCH TO BE ABLE TO USE SAME BLOCK SIZE \, OR TO USE A TABRECEIVE~ OBJECT TO READ FROM TABLE INSTEAD OF INLET~, f 94;
#X text 10 518 WHEN PHASE IS RESET AND AND PARENT DSP IS STARTED \, I CAN BE SURE THAT IT STARTS FROM 0 PHASE. NOW WHEN I CALCULATE ONE BLOCK OF FFT \, IT COULD BE THAT FIRST BLOCK AT THE INLET IS NOT THE FIRST BLOCK OF OSC~ GENERATION AND i ACCEPT THIS. BUT WHY FROM THE NEXT BANGS THAT I DO SPORADICALLY \, ALWAYS PHASE OF FFT OUTPUT(SEEN FROM REAL/IMAG) REMAINS THE SAME? AS IF FFT HAS A MEMORY! -> PROBABLY NOT VERY IMPORTANT BUT BETTER TO INVESTIGATE, f 103;
#X text 9 663 BUT CONSIDER THAT I AM NOT GOING TO DO REAL-TIME PHASE VOCODING -> EASIER AND I THINK NOW ISSUES WILL BE THERE, f 112;
#X text 11 696 WHEN TABWRITE~ IS BANGED \, IT WAIT FOR (WINDOW-SIZE = 512) SAMPLE TO COME AND THEN DRAWS THEM OF THE WINDOW!, f 108;
#X text 22 34 IF PARENT AND SUBPATCH SHARE BLOCKSIZE (512 IN THIS CASE) \, PHASE WILL BE CONSISTENTLY CORRECT. IF PARENT 64 AND SUBPATCH 512 \, FFT CAN GENERATE DIFFERENT PHASES...SOMETHING WITH THE BLOCK BUFFERING \; tabreceive~ OBJECT READING THE INPUT TO FFT DIRECTLY FROM INPUT ARRAY \$0-input WILL NO HAVE THIS ISSUE AND WORKS FINE!, f 147;
